		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=325931"><span id="">digigaran</span></a><b><span id=""></span></b><br />6 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=digigaran&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>I have found it extremely handy to use /stopsong before the /melody command.&nbsp;&nbsp;This way you dont have to smack the button twice to restart the melody if you snare/slow doesnt stick on the first cast. <br /> <br />NOTE on twisting:  Obviously twisting is the most beneficial use of a bard's time, however, not really worth the effort if you are not using the correct instrument modifier.  I have found great power in the Bandoliers, which were introduced with DoN (oh the glory).  Setup a bandolier for your weapons, and setup one for your 3 most used instruments.  I usually have percussion, string, and wind loaded.  Your modifier is checked only at the END of your song cast, so pop in the correct instrument with a hotkey at the end of your song for maximum song effectiveness.  I also swap my weapons in between casts to give me that extra few swings of melee on my mainhand, mostly for the procs. <br /> <br /> <br />---Be kind to the lesser classes, they can't help their weaknesses. <br /> <br />Grozan of Tunare</p>
